Aug 20 2009 	Greatest Disappointment Of Our Lives	Having stayed at the Campton Place for many years while it was still among the greatest of European-style boutique hotels in the U.S., our experience with the hotel under new ownership has ruined it for us. The Taj Hotel group has allowed standards to slip below an acceptable level for a luxury property. The woodwork showed highly visible signs of wear and careless maintenace on almost every floor. The suite we occupied was dilapidated with scars on the woodwork, doors and drawers that no longer closed properly and signs of lapsed attention to detail wherever we looked. Banquette cushions were positioned with the zipper side facing the room instead of the wall. The flowers near the elevator were wilted and the atmosphere beyond the well-appointed lobby felt ill-used and dingy where it had always been immaculate under the old ownership. There were scratches on the interior and exterior of the elevators and one of the two elevators was out of commission for a portion of our shortened stay (we checked out early and took refuge at the Ritz Carlton which was the same price). We also noted that the staff had a poorer attitude and lower level of training than before. Neither was the restaurant the hospitable oasis it had been for so many years. The hostess was very picky about whether we had a reservation and was reluctant to seat us at an available booth when requested. The complimentary breakfast newspapers were no longer present. The service was appallingly slow, but the food was still impeccably prepared and wonderful as it has always been, even if it took forever to get it. While the hotel still has pretensions to being a world class property, first hand experience argues otherwise and we would encourage visitors to choose any other luxury property before risking the type of disappointment we encountered. At premium prices, you deserve a first class experience which ours most certainly was not.	
